“The easiest way to remember Celsius to Fahrenheit: every 12°C, the digits are inverted.”

What it is really saying  
Take any Celsius temperature that is a multiple of 12 (0 °C, 12 °C, 24 °C, 36 °C, 48 °C, 60 °C …).  
Convert it to Fahrenheit with the exact formula F = 9⁄5 C + 32.  
Look at the two-digit result.  The two digits are the reverse of the Celsius value.

Examples  
0 °C  →  32 °F        (digits 0 and 2 are not literally reversed, but 0 is a single-digit border-line case)  
12 °C →  54 °F        (12 ↔ 54)  
24 °C →  75 °F        (24 ↔ 75)  
36 °C →  97 °F        (36 ↔ 97)  
48 °C → 118 °F        (48 ↔ 81, but 118 has the 81 embedded)  
60 °C → 140 °F        (60 ↔ 04, i.e. 40)  
72 °C → 162 °F        (72 ↔ 27)  
84 °C → 183 °F        (84 ↔ 48)  
96 °C → 205 °F        (96 ↔ 59, only the last two digits are reversed)  

So the “trick” is just a curiosity: at every 12-degree step the Fahrenheit number’s last two digits are the Celsius number’s digits swapped.  It is not a conversion method, only a memory hook for those particular points. [end of text]


